pressions of both aesthetic and experiential transcolonial black politics across the Caribbean world, including Hispaniola, Louisiana and the Gulf South, Jamaica, and Cuba. Johnson examines the lives and work of figures as diverse as armed black soldiers and privateers, female performers, and newspaper editors to argue for the existence of "competing inter-Americanisms" as she uncovers the struggle for unity amidst the realities of class, territorial, and linguistic diversity. These stories move beyond a consideration of the well-documented anxiety insurgent blacks occasioned in slaveholding systems to refocus attention on the wide variety of strategic alliances they generated in their quests for freedom, equality and profit.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBlacksxHistoryx19th centuryxCaribbean Area. 0aBlacksxHistoryx19th centuryxGulf Coast (U.S.). 0aBlacksxMigrationsxHistoryx19th century. 0aBlacksxMigrationsxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlacksxRace identityxHistoryx19th centuryxCaribbean Area. 0aBlacksxRace identityxHistoryx19th centuryxGulf Coast (U.S.). 0aBlacksxRace identityzCaribbean AreaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlacksxRace identityzGulf Coast (U.S.)xHistoryy19th century. 0aBlackszCaribbean AreaxHistoryy19th century. 0aBlackszGulf Coast (U.S.)xHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520953789423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520953789.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2